    <div class="csc-header csc-header-n1"><h1 class="csc-firstHeader">Hermann Gundert</h1></div>
    <!--  Header: [end] -->

    <!--  Text: [begin] -->
    <p class="bodytext">Hermann Gundert (1814 - 1893) studied Theology in  Tübingen, where he also learned Sanskrit. Here he obtained his Dr. phil.  in 1835. Later he went to England and studied various Indian languages,  as Bengali, Telugu, Marathi, and Urdu.
    </p>
    <p class="bodytext">In 1838 he started working for the Basel Mission in  Nettur in a Malayalam-speaking area. He established a Malayalam school  and focused on the analysis of the Malayalam language: It was in fact  he, who wrote the first Malayalam Grammar - a copy of the first version  from 1851 belongs to this collection [CiXIV 35] and a Malayalam-English  Dictionary that is still in use [CiXIV 68]; among Gundert’s pioneering  contributions there is also the introduction of the use of the cil sign  (˘) into Malayalam script <i>[ref. to article by Wiki-media people]</i>–  and the differentiation between long “e” േ and short “e” െ. Moreover,  his role as missionery brought him to translate the bible in Malayalam  and other religious texts, such the books of psalms. Due to health  issues he left India in 1859, and brought forward his research interests  in the family village of Calw  </p>
