<div id="c22" class="csc-default">
    <!--  Header: [begin] -->
    <div class="csc-header csc-header-n2"><h1>Legacy</h1></div>
    <!--  Header: [end] -->

    <!--  Text: [begin] -->
    <div class="csc-textpic-text"><p class="bodytext">All Gundert’s  interests are mirrored in his legacy: Gundert’s collection entails both  grammars and primers as well as many religious texts. Yet, to frame the  missioner’s intellectual enterprise within these two topic, would be a  to misunderstand this great savant. He was trying to comprehend an  entire culture, and not just bits and bites, and indeed in his legacy,  we find also modern novels - such as the famous <i>Indulekha</i>, which is, along with <i>Kundalatā</i>  considered as the first Malayalam novel; in addition to the new  developments of the literary production at his time, he collected also  old texts of the Sanskritic and Malayali traditions – thus, part of his  legacy are, for instance, a copy of the Sanskrit text <i>Vajrasūcī</i>, with a Malayalam commentary, or the <i>Kṛṣṇagatha</i>, a well-known Malayalam traditional poetical narration of Kṛṣṇa life.
        </p>
        <p class="bodytext">Gundert was specially interested in the historical development of Kerala and so we find several copies of the&nbsp; <i>Kerala Pazhama</i> <i><i>and </i></i><i>Keralolpati.<br /></i>
        </p>
        <p class="bodytext">Among the Kannaḍa texts, there is the Bibliotheca  Carnatica, a series of editions, initiated by his colleague and freind  Hermann Mögling, that was meant to encompass the most important works of  the Kannaḍa traditions. The series was never finished, but the first 5  volumes entail texts that are fundamental to the religious and  intellectual history of South India, as the Viraśaiva hagiography of the  poet and religious revolutionary, Basava, the <i>Cannabasava Purāṇa</i> or the most popular Kannada adaptation of the Indian epic <i>Mahābhārata</i>, the <i>Karnata Bharata </i>of Kumāravyasa.
        </p>
        <p class="bodytext">A text that could be of great interest not only for  linguists, but also for the scholars of religious and cultural studies  are for sure the Latin-Kannaḍa / Kannaḍa-Latin Dictionaries compiled for  the Missions in Mysore.</p></div>
